				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body ve-init-mw-desktopArticleT=
arget-targetContainer" aria-labelledby=3D"firstHeading" data-mw-ve-target-c=
ontainer=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistical considerations on how many observations to make</div>
<p><b>Sample size determination</b> or <b>estimation</b> is the act of choo=
sing the number of observations or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Replication_(statistics)" title=3D"Replication (statistics)">replicates</a=
> to include in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_samp=
le" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical sample">statistical sample</=
a>. The sample size is an important feature of any empirical study in which=
 the goal is to make <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_i=
nference" title=3D"Statistical inference">inferences</a> about a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_population" title=3D"Statistical=
 population">population</a> from a sample. In practice, the sample size use=
d in a study is usually determined based on the cost, time, or convenience =
of collecting the data, and the need for it to offer sufficient <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_power" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Statistical power">statistical power</a>. In complex studies, differen=
t sample sizes may be allocated, such as in stratified surveys or experimen=
tal designs with multiple treatment groups. In a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Census" title=3D"Census">census</a>, data is sought for an e=
ntire population, hence the intended sample size is equal to the population=
. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experimental_design" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Experimental design">experimental design</a>, where =
a study may be divided into different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Treatment_group" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Treatment group">treatm=
ent groups</a>, there may be different sample sizes for each group.
</p><p>Sample sizes may be chosen in several ways:
</p>
<ul><li>using experience =E2=80=93 small samples, though sometimes unavoida=
ble, can result in wide <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence=
_interval" title=3D"Confidence interval">confidence intervals</a> and risk =
of errors in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesi=
s_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">s=
tatistical hypothesis testing</a>.</li>
<li>using a target variance for an estimate to be derived from the sample e=
ventually obtained, i.e., if a high precision is required (narrow confidenc=
e interval) this translates to a low target variance of the estimator.</li>
<li>the use of a power target, i.e. the power of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Statistical hypothesis testing">statistical test</a> to be applied once=
 the sample is collected.</li>
<li>using a confidence level, i.e. the larger the required confidence level=
, the larger the sample size (given a constant precision requirement).</li>=
</ul>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Introduction">Introduction<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_=
determination&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Int=
roduction"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>Sample size determination is a crucial aspect of research methodology th=
at plays a significant role in ensuring the reliability and validity of stu=
dy findings. In order to influence the accuracy of estimates, the power of =
statistical tests, and the general robustness of the research findings, it =
entails carefully choosing the number of participants or data points to be =
included in a study.
</p><p>Consider the case where we are conducting a survey to determine the =
average satisfaction level of customers regarding a new product. To determi=
ne an appropriate sample size, we  need to consider factors such as the des=
ired level of confidence, margin of error, and variability in the responses=
. We might decide that we want a 95% confidence level, meaning we are 95% c=
onfident that the true average satisfaction level falls within the calculat=
ed range. We also decide on a margin of error, of =C2=B13%, which indicates=
 the acceptable range of difference between our sample estimate and the tru=
e population parameter. Additionally, we may have some idea of the expected=
 variability in satisfaction levels based on previous data or assumptions.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Importance">Importance</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_dete=
rmination&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Importa=
nce"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<p>Larger sample sizes generally lead to increased <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy_and_precision" title=3D"Accuracy and precision">p=
recision</a> when <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_esti=
mation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical estimation">estimating</=
a> unknown parameters. For instance, to accurately determine the prevalence=
 of pathogen infection in a specific species of fish, it is preferable to e=
xamine a sample of 200 fish rather than 100 fish.  Several fundamental fact=
s of mathematical statistics describe this phenomenon, including the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_large_numbers" title=3D"Law of la=
rge numbers">law of large numbers</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Central limit theorem">central =
limit theorem</a>.
</p><p>In some situations, the increase in precision for larger sample size=
s is minimal, or even non-existent. This can result from the presence of <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systematic_error" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Systematic error">systematic errors</a> or strong <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_and_dependence" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Correlation and dependence">dependence</a> in the data, or if =
the data follows a heavy-tailed distribution, or because the data is strong=
ly dependent or biased.
</p><p>Sample sizes may be evaluated by the quality of the resulting estima=
tes, as follows. It is usually determined on the basis of the cost, time or=
 convenience of data collection and the need for sufficient statistical pow=
er. For example, if a proportion is being estimated, one may wish to have t=
he 95% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confidence_interval" title=
=3D"Confidence interval">confidence interval</a> be less than 0.06 units wi=
de.  Alternatively, sample size may be assessed based on the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_power" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Statistical power">power</a> of a hypothesis test. For example, if we a=
re comparing the support for a certain political candidate among women with=
 the support for that candidate among men, we may wish to have 80% power to=
 detect a difference in the support levels of 0.04 units.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Estimation">Estimation</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_dete=
rmination&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Estimat=
ion"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></=
span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Estimation_of_a_proportion"=
>Estimation of a proportion</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DSample_size_determination&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
4" title=3D"Edit section: Estimation of a proportion"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_proportion" title=3D"=
Population proportion">Population proportion</a></div>
<p>A relatively simple situation is estimation of a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Proportionality_(mathematics)" title=3D"Proportionality (=
mathematics)">proportion</a>. It is a fundamental aspect of statistical ana=
lysis, particularly when gauging the prevalence of a specific characteristi=
c within a population. For example, we may wish to estimate the proportion =
of residents in a community who are at least 65 years old.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estimator" title=3D"Est=
imator">estimator</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proport=
ionality_(mathematics)" title=3D"Proportionality (mathematics)">proportion<=
/a> is <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 {\hat {p}}=3DX/n}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mover>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">^<!-- ^ --></mo>
            </mover>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>X</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>n</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\hat {p}}=3D=
X/n}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bf5d898a07e3f77cf494d9f9de94ef2eaa684acd" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; margin-left: -0.089ex; width:9.084ex; height:2.843ex;" al=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\hat {p}}=3DX/n}"></span>, where <i>X</i> is the numbe=
r of 'positive' instances (e.g., the number of people out of the <i>n</i> s=
ampled people who are at least 65 years old). When the observations are <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_(statistics)" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Independent (statistics)">independent</a>, this estimat=
or has a (scaled) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distrib=
ution" title=3D"Binomial distribution">binomial distribution</a> (and is al=
so the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_(statistics)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample (statistics)">sample</a> <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_mean" title=3D"Arithmetic mean">mean</a>=
 of data from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernoulli_distribu=
tion" title=3D"Bernoulli distribution">Bernoulli distribution</a>). The max=
imum <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Variance">=
variance</a> of this distribution is 0.25, which occurs when the true <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parameter" title=3D"Parameter">paramete=
r</a> is <i>p</i> =3D 0.5. In practical applications, where the true parame=
ter <i>p</i> is unknown, the maximum variance is often employed for sample =
size assessments.  If a reasonable estimate for p is known the quantity <sp=
an class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle p(1-p)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>p</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle p(1-p)}</anno=
tation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/0ed46dfa9389f683b4f6d19811579e2576dd0e96" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; margin-left: -0.089ex; width:8.24ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=
=3D"{\displaystyle p(1-p)}"></span> may be used in place of 0.25.
</p><p>As the sample size <i>n</i> grows sufficiently large, the distributi=
on of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><=
math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle=
 {\hat {p}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
