            <mover>
              <mi>p</mi>
              <mo stretchy=3D"false">^<!-- ^ --></mo>
            </mover>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\hat {p}}}</=
annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/8bd4c026f1b3413adc58b9b65e89e62bce92c85a" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; margin-left: -0.089ex; width:1.449ex; height:2.509ex;" al=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\hat {p}}}"></span> will be closely approximated by a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distribution" title=3D"Norm=
al distribution">normal distribution</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_size_determination=
#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Using this and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution#Confidence_intervals" title=3D"Binomial dis=
tribution">Wald method for the binomial distribution</a>, yields a confiden=
ce interval, with Z representing the standard Z-score for the desired confi=
dence level (e.g., 1.96 for a 95% confidence interval), in the form:
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e \left({\widehat {p}}-Z{\sqrt {\frac {0.25}{n}}},\quad {\widehat {p}}+Z{\s=
