              <mn>6</mn>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>96.04</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle {\frac {4\tim=
es 1.96^{2}\times 15^{2}}{6^{2}}}=3D96.04}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/9e1774476d06c06e4700c63f3b3a651c6a6fe7bb" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -2.338ex; width:24.642ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
frac {4\times 1.96^{2}\times 15^{2}}{6^{2}}}=3D96.04}"></span>, which would=
 be rounded up to 97, since sample sizes must be integers and must meet or =
exceed the calculated <i>minimum</i> value. Understanding these calculation=
s is essential for researchers designing studies to accurately estimate pop=
ulation means within a desired level of confidence.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Required_sample_sizes_for_h=
ypothesis_tests">Required sample sizes for hypothesis tests <span class=3D"=
anchor" id=3D"Estimating_sample_sizes"></span></h2><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_determination&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Required sample sizes for hypot=
hesis tests"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>One of the prevalent challenges faced by statisticians revolves around t=
he task of calculating the sample size needed to attain a specified statist=
ical power for a test, all while maintaining a pre-determined <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ty=
pe I error">Type I error</a> rate =CE=B1, which signifies the level of sign=
ificance in hypothesis testing. It yields a certain <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_power" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statist=
ical power">power</a> for a test, given a predetermined. As follows, this c=
an be estimated by pre-determined tables for certain values, by formulas, b=
y simulation, by Mead's resource equation, or by the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumulative_distribution_function" title=3D"Cumulative di=
stribution function">cumulative distribution function</a>:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tables">Tables</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_determinatio=
n&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Tables"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
