<p>The table shown on the right can be used in a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Two-sample_t-test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Two-sample=
 t-test">two-sample t-test</a> to estimate the sample sizes of an <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Experimental_group" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Experimental group">experimental group</a> and a <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_group" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cont=
rol group">control group</a> that are of equal size, that is, the total num=
ber of individuals in the trial is twice that of the number given, and the =
desired <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Significance_level" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Significance level">significance level</a> is 0.0=
5.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kenny1987_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_size_determination#cite_note-Kenny1987-4"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> The parameters used are:
</p>
<ul><li>The desired <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_po=
wer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical power">statistical power</a=
> of the trial, shown in column to the left.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cohen%27s_d" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Cohen's d">Cohen's d</a> (=3D&nbsp;effect size), which is the=
 expected difference between the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
ean" title=3D"Mean">means</a> of the target values between the experimental=
 group and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_group" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Control group">control group</a>, divided by the=
 expected <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation" titl=
e=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Formulas">Formulas</h3><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_determin=
ation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Formulas"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Calculating a required sample size is often not easy since the distribut=
ion of the test statistic under the alternative hypothesis of interest is u=
sually hard to work with. Approximate sample size formulas for specific pro=
blems are available - some general references are=20
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Sample_size_determination#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
and
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Sample_size_determination#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"A_computational_approach_(Q=
uickSize)"><span id=3D"A_computational_approach_.28QuickSize.29"></span>A c=
omputational approach (QuickSize)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_determination&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D9" title=3D"Edit section: A computational approach (QuickSize)"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The QuickSize algorithm
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Sample_size_determination#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
is a very general approach that is simple to use yet versatile enough to gi=
ve an exact solution for a broad range of problems. It uses simulation toge=
ther with a search algorithm.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Mead's_resource_equation"><=
span id=3D"Mead.27s_resource_equation"></span>Mead's resource equation</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSample_size_dete=
rmination&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Mead's=
 resource equation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roger_Mead" title=3D"Roger Mead=
">Mead</a>'s resource equation is often used for estimating sample sizes of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laboratory_animal" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Laboratory animal">laboratory animals</a>, as well as in m=
any other laboratory experiments. It may not be as accurate as using other =
methods in estimating sample size, but gives a hint of what is the appropri=
ate sample size where parameters such as expected standard deviations or ex=
pected differences in values between groups are unknown or very hard to est=
imate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hubrecht&amp;Kirkwood2010_8-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_size_determination#cite_n=
ote-Hubrecht&amp;Kirkwood2010-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>All the parameters in the equation are in fact the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degrees_of_freedom_(statistics)" title=3D"Degrees o=
f freedom (statistics)">degrees of freedom</a> of the number of their conce=
pts, and hence, their numbers are subtracted by 1 before insertion into the=
 equation.
</p><p>The equation is:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Hubrecht&amp;Kirkwood2010_8-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_size_det=
ermination#cite_note-Hubrecht&amp;Kirkwood2010-8"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyl=
e E=3DN-B-T,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>E</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>N</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>B</mi>
        <mo>=E2=88=92<!-- =E2=88=92 --></mo>
        <mi>T</mi>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle E=3DN-B-T,}</=
annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/f5597c7339179510cb97b75785958c2f57214807" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:16.666ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle E=
=3DN-B-T,}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where:
</p>
<ul><li><i>N</i> is the total number of individuals or units in the study (=
minus 1)</li>
<li><i>B</i> is the <i>blocking component</i>, representing environmental e=
ffects allowed for in the design (minus 1)</li>
<li><i>T</i> is the <i>treatment component</i>, corresponding to the number=
 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treatment_groups" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Treatment groups">treatment groups</a> (including <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Control_group" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Control group">control group</a>) being used, or the number of questi=
ons being asked (minus 1)</li>
<li><i>E</i> is the degrees of freedom of the <i>error component and</i> sh=
ould be somewhere between 10 and 20.</li></ul>
<p>For example, if a study using laboratory animals is planned with four tr=
eatment groups (<i>T</i>=3D3), with eight animals per group, making 32 anim=
als total (<i>N</i>=3D31), without any further <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Stratified_sampling" title=3D"Stratified sampling">stratificat=
ion</a> (<i>B</i>=3D0), then <i>E</i> would equal 28, which is above the cu=
toff of 20, indicating that sample size may be a bit too large, and six ani=
mals per group might be more appropriate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_size_determination=
#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cumulative_distribution_fun=
ction">Cumulative distribution function</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection">=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
